Rating: 4
This is the best. You'll never want to go back to regular ketchup. I use it with a sloppy joe recipe from an earlier Gourmet and it is FABULOUS. The recipe is not on this site so I'll give it here Saute 1 lb ground chuck with 1/2 c chopped onion. Stir in 1cup ketchup; 1 tablespoon (each) white vinegar, lemon juice, Worcestershire sauch, dark brown sugar; 1 teaspoon (each) Dijon mustard, paprika; salt and pepper to taste. Cook uncovered until thickened, about 30 minutes. Divide among 4 hamburger buns

Rating: 2
As an Atkins dieter, I wanted to try this as an alternative to commercial ketchup, which is loaded w/ corn syrup. I substituted Splenda in place of the sugar & omitted the Tabasco (since when does ketchup have Tabasco in it?). The only time consuming part of the recipe is forcing the puree thru a food mill, but overall, I was amazed at how good this tastes! I'm also going to use this in homemade BBQ sauce. Yummy!

